mexican salamander threatened with extinction the leopold leadership program skip to main content search this site the leopold leadership program about fellows news fellowship information resources fellows login home 2013 fellowship information all cohort reunion save the date june 19 21 2012 in this section 2012 newsletters newsletter archive mexican salamander threatened with extinction luis zambrano gonzalez published on september 25 2009 zambrano gonzalez the population of axolotl a salamander noted for its unusual life cycle and appearance has plummeted 90 in the past four years according to a new study co authored by luis zambrano 2009 wild only in the xochimilco region the axolotl is losing its habitat to urban expansion from mexico city declining water quality and competition with nonnative fish for food are the main causes for the reduced numbers the authors say read recent coverage by the bbc and scientific american tags amphibians extinction urbanization 2012 leopold leadership program the stanford woods institute for the environment stanford university stanford ca 94305
